# SETUP.md — Heart Materials AI

A step-by-step guide to installing every tool and library required to run `app.py`.

---

## What the App Uses

These are the external tools and libraries imported directly by the app:

| Library / Tool | What it does in this app |
|---|---|
| **Ollama** | Runs the local LLM (`llama3.1:8b`) on your machine |
| **LlamaIndex** | RAG framework — splits PDFs, builds the query engine |
| **ChromaDB** | Vector database that stores document embeddings on disk |
| **Sentence Transformers** | Embedding model (`all-MiniLM-L6-v2`) used to index PDFs |
| **Streamlit** | Serves the chat UI in your browser |
| **pandas** | Powers the materials knowledge base CSV ranking |

---

## Requirements

- macOS (Apple Silicon recommended) or Windows
- Python 3.12
- ~5 GB of free disk space (for the LLM model)

---

## Step 1 — Install Python 3.12

### macOS

```bash
# Install Homebrew if you don't have it
/bin/bash -c "$(curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Homebrew/install/HEAD/install.sh)"

# Install Python 3.12
brew install python@3.12
```

### Windows

Download the installer from [python.org](https://www.python.org/downloads/release/python-3120/) and run it.

> ⚠️ Check **"Add Python to PATH"** during installation before clicking Install.

Verify either way:

```bash
python3 --version
# Expected: Python 3.12.x
```

---

## Step 2 — Clone the Repository

```bash
git clone https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/heart-materials-ai.git
cd heart-materials-ai
```

---

## Step 3 — Create a Virtual Environment

This keeps the project's packages isolated from your system Python.

```bash
python3 -m venv venv

# Activate — macOS/Linux
source venv/bin/activate

# Activate — Windows
venv\Scripts\activate
```

You should see `(venv)` at the start of your terminal prompt.

---

## Step 4 — Install Python Dependencies

Install all required libraries in one command:

```bash
pip install \
  streamlit \
  pandas \
  chromadb \
  llama-index-core \
  llama-index-vector-stores-chroma \
  llama-index-llms-ollama \
  llama-index-embeddings-huggingface \
  sentence-transformers
```

What each package maps to in `app.py`:

| pip package | Import in app.py |
|---|---|
| `streamlit` | `import streamlit as st` |
| `pandas` | `import pandas as pd` |
| `chromadb` | `import chromadb` |
| `llama-index-core` | `from llama_index.core import VectorStoreIndex, SimpleDirectoryReader, ...` |
| `llama-index-vector-stores-chroma` | `from llama_index.vector_stores.chroma import ChromaVectorStore` |
| `llama-index-llms-ollama` | `from llama_index.llms.ollama import Ollama` |
| `llama-index-embeddings-huggingface` | `from llama_index.embeddings.huggingface import HuggingFaceEmbedding` |
| `sentence-transformers` | Used by HuggingFaceEmbedding to load `all-MiniLM-L6-v2` |

Alternatively, if the repo has a `requirements.txt`:

```bash
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

---

## Step 5 — Install Ollama

Ollama runs the language model locally. No API key or internet connection is needed after setup.

### macOS

Download from [https://ollama.com/download](https://ollama.com/download) and run the `.dmg`, or install via Homebrew:

```bash
brew install ollama
```

### Windows

Download and run the installer from [https://ollama.com/download](https://ollama.com/download).

---

## Step 6 — Download the LLM Model

The app defaults to `llama3.1:8b`. Pull it with:

```bash
ollama pull llama3.1:8b
```

This is a one-time download (~4.7 GB). Once complete, verify it's available:

```bash
ollama list
# llama3.1:8b should appear in the list
```

> **Want a different model?** You can type any model name from [ollama.com/library](https://ollama.com/library) into the "Ollama model name" field in the app sidebar — just make sure you've run `ollama pull <model-name>` first.

---

## Step 7 — Start Ollama

Ollama needs to be running in the background before launching the app.

### macOS
If you installed via the `.dmg`, Ollama runs automatically. If not, start it manually:

```bash
ollama serve
```

### Windows
Ollama starts automatically as a background service after installation.

---

## Step 8 — Run the App

With your virtual environment active and Ollama running:

```bash
streamlit run app/app.py
```

Then open your browser to:

```
http://localhost:8501
```

---

## Project Folder Structure

The `data/`, `kb/`, and `chroma_db/` folders are created automatically on first run.

```
heart-materials-ai/
│
├── app/
│   └── app.py
│
├── data/             ← your uploaded PDFs go here
├── kb/               ← auto-generated materials CSVs
├── chroma_db/        ← auto-generated vector index
│
├── requirements.txt
└── SETUP.md
```

---

## Troubleshooting

**`ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'llama_index'`**
Your virtual environment is not active. Run `source venv/bin/activate` (macOS) or `venv\Scripts\activate` (Windows) before installing or running the app.

**`Connection refused` when querying**
Ollama is not running. Open a separate terminal and run `ollama serve`.

**`model not found` error in the app**
You haven't pulled the model yet. Run `ollama pull llama3.1:8b` (or whichever model name you entered in the sidebar).

**Slow on first query**
The first run downloads the `all-MiniLM-L6-v2` embedding model from HuggingFace automatically (~90 MB). This only happens once and is cached locally afterward.

**ChromaDB errors after changing PDFs**
Click **Build / Rebuild Index** in the sidebar to regenerate the vector database from scratch.

---

## Summary Checklist

- [ ] Python 3.12 installed
- [ ] Repository cloned
- [ ] Virtual environment created and activated
- [ ] Python packages installed via pip
- [ ] Ollama installed
- [ ] `llama3.1:8b` model pulled
- [ ] Ollama running in the background
- [ ] App launched with `streamlit run app/app.py`
